The '''Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf classification system''' is an evolving system of classification of [[vegetation type]]s, [[plant communities]], or [[floristic characterization]].<ref name=ICPL>Introduction to California Plant Life, [[Robert Ornduff]], [[Phyllis M. Faber]], Todd Keeler-Wolf, California Natural History Guides No. 69, University of California Press, Ltd., 2003, {{ISBN|978-0-520-23704-9}}</ref>{{rp|114, 138-9}}<ref>Santa Margartia River Recharge and Recovery Enhancement Program, United States Bureau of Reclamation, [http://www.usbr.gov/lc/socal/reports/SMCUPPermit15000/Part1.pdf]</ref><ref>Biological Resources Report, Elder and Plunge Creek Project, San Bernardino County Department of Public Works Environmental Management Division, [http://www.sbcounty.gov/dpw/public_notices/pdf/Plunge-Creek/Appendix-C1.pdf]</ref><ref>Placer County Natural Resources Report, Chapter 2: Methods, 2004</ref><ref>Todd Keeler-Wolfe bio, California Native Plant Society, [http://www.cnps.org/cnps/education/workshops/instructors.php]</ref> It was first developed in 1995 by [[John O. Sawyer]] and [[Todd Keeler-Wolf]] for the [[California Native Plant Society]], in the mission to classify all vegetation in [[California]].<ref name=ICPL/>{{rp|114}} Particular attention was paid to recognizing rare types that were "lumped" into general categories in previous systems, such as the [[Munz and Keck classification system]], [[Chetham and Haller classification system]], and [[Holland classification system]].<ref name=ICPL/>{{rp|114}} It uses constantly updated quantitative measurements of both species diversity and cover to define its types.<ref name=ICPL/>{{rp|114}} It intended to be evolving and to continue to be refined.<ref name=ICPL/>{{rp|114}}  

